article.description:
Karl Malone scored 21 points, including 16 in the
second half, and the Utah Jazz handed the Denver Nuggets their
fifth straight loss with a 96-79 victory Wednesday night.
article.headline: Jazz close in on .500 with rout of Nuggets
article.linkText: Malone, Jazz easily hand Nuggets fifth straight loss
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Denver took 22 more shots than Utah, had a 23-9 advantage in offensive rebounds and forced the Jazz into a season-high 31 turnovers. Still, the Nuggets came up short.
Malone

Poor shooting will do that to a team. Utah shot 59 percent, compared to Denver's 31 percent, in handing the Nuggets their fifth straight loss, 96-79 on Wednesday night. Karl Malone scored 21 points, including 16 in the second half, and added 10 rebounds and five assists. The Jazz posted their third straight win and climbed within one game of .500 at 6-7. Matt Harpring added 20 points, John Stockton had 15 points and 11 assists, and Andrei Kirilenko came off the bench to score 16 for the Jazz. Juwan Howard led the Nuggets with 17 points and 13 rebounds, and James Posey added 14 points. "It's our inability to hit open shots,'' Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "Until we find a way to put the ball in the basket, we are going to keep coming up short. We had 23 offensive boards and only 11 second-chance points.'' The Jazz shot 75 percent in the first quarter and 58 percent in the final period, overcoming a brutal schedule that had them playing their seventh game in 10 days. Coach Jerry Sloan attributed the high turnover total to fatigue. "I think our energy level fell off a little bit,'' he said. "That is to be expected in a situation like that -- seven games in 10 days and a lot of travel. "We committed a lot of offensive fouls. We were running over people. That is a little indicative of us being tired. We tried to find a short cut to get the game over with and win it.'' Leading 53-41 at halftime, the Jazz took control with a 12-3 run -- including eight straight points -- to open the third quarter. Harpring's two layups sandwiched Malone's four free throws during the 8-0 spurt which produced a 65-44 lead, and the Nuggets got no closer than 12 after that. Malone, who had nine points in the third, praised the play of new additions Harpring and Calbert Cheaney, who scored 10 points. "Those guys are really helping us out,'' Malone said. "Whenever you can have guys like that come in and give you a lift, it's really good. That is why they sign free agents like Calbert. We'll get better as the season goes on.'' Sloan said Harpring "does a number of things well. He rebounds, he runs the floor, he can post up inside, he goes after offensive rebounds. He's just a good basketball player. I think he'll get better as he gets more comfortable with what we are trying to do.'' The Jazz shot 75 percent (12 of 16) in the first quarter and were 8-of-8 on free throws, but led only 32-26 at the end of the period. Harpring had nine points in the quarter, including seven straight Utah points. Kirilenko scored 10 points in the second quarter, helping Utah open up a 13-point lead. Kirilenko had eight of Utah's first 10 points in the period, capped by a three-point play that made it 42-32. Kirilenko's tip-in, Stockton's 20-foot jumper and Harpring's free throw put Utah ahead 52-39 with 1:25 left in the period. Howard had 10 points in the first half for Denver. For a 5-minute span late in the third quarter and early in the fourth, the Nuggets -- the NBA's youngest team -- fielded a lineup of second-year pro Chris Andersen and four rookies -- Nene Hilario, Nikoloz Tskitishvili, Junior Harrington and Predrag Savovic. Savovic had 11 points and four assists in his NBA debut. Game notes
The Nuggets placed point guard Chris Whitney (sprained left ankle) on the injured list and activated Savovic from the injured list. ... Jazz guard Mark Jackson was part of a June trade that brought Marcus Camby to Denver in exchange for Antonio McDyess. Jackson, unhappy with the trade, was waived in September and signed with Utah. ... Denver, the NBA's lowest-scoring team, has scored fewer than 80 points in eight of its 11 games, including its last five games, all losses. ... Utah's .590 shooting percentage was the second-best in the NBA this season, trailing only Denver's .592 at Portland on Nov. 2. ... The Nuggets used their ninth different starting lineup in 11 games.
